begin_memory_text: My partner and I talked about our different cultures, travel history, family, current COVID situation, working in the current climate, immigration, visas, traveling, and guns.
middle_memory_text: I was explaining how my family and I communicate considering that we live in different parts of the world. He was also telling me about his family.
end_memory_text: I was explaining to him how foreigners navigate and travel. The immigration requirements and processes. My partner was sympathizing with my experiences. We also talked about the struggles that immigration imposes on people.
rest_of_day_open: The week is going to be quiet and very productive. I see myself focused on work and accomplishing my goals. I also expect the week to be filled with a lot of planning and shopping for necessities. I expect to spend most of the week indoors, working on my laptop.
critical_positive: My partner and I took turns asking each other questions and we both actively listen to each other. Our conversation was interesting because we are from different cultures and we took the time to somewhat learn about each other's experiences. Lastly, my partner and I were empathetic toward each other.
critical_negative: I thought that everything worked well. We both equally contributed to the conversation. We both asked questions. We were both attentive and considerate. My partner and I kept the conversation interesting and flowing. We did not have many awkward moments except for the first 30 seconds, which is understandable considering we are strangers.

begin_memory_text: I first asked her where she was from. I remember feeling a bit bad about the question immediately afterwards because it turned out she was foreign. I was just curious to see what part of the US she was calling from as I assumed (incorrectly) that all the participants were American.
middle_memory_text: We talked about her life in Texas. She was a student coming from Zimbabwe, so we discussed what it was like living in the US, her family situation, how often she gets to see her mother and brothers in England, or her sister in Australia.
end_memory_text: We ended up talking about how she feels about guns. She does not have a permit and has only seen guns while at Walmart. Her boyfriend told her owns two but has agreed not to take them out because she's afraid of them. Before the US she had only seen a gun in Zimbabwe when her farmer grandfather showed what he used to hunt. She also mentioned her boyfriend moved from Chicago down to Texas to sort of escape the life he was living. It seemed he had been hanging around the wrong crowds and was destined for trouble
rest_of_day_open: About average, to be honest. I don't really have anything too big or important coming up. Standard work week. The weather seems like it's going to continue to be lousy until the weekend. I guess that doesn't matter too much as I'm home almost all the time now. I just hope I can book my rental car for Thanksgiving for not too much because that will get my wife off my back!
critical_positive: As with most conversations, people like speaking about themselves. I'm one of the few that really doesn't like divulging too much personal information. I always feel uncomfortable talking about myself, for a variety of reasons. But if I simply pose a few well-timed questions that show I'm listening and care about what the other is saying, they'll be happy to tell me their life story.
critical_negative: I asked her where she was from, which opened up discussion about her home country of Zimbabwe, plus the cultural differences between our nations. Then I asked about her family. She has a bunch of siblings, some in England, some in Australia. So we chatted about how often they get to meet up.
